<br>
I wholeheartedly support the last comment. All too often (just look at EQ where the system is completely biased towards the ideal, ultraspecialized group, Cleric, Fighter, Rogue trio), &quot;jack of all trade&quot; character types just don't work, because, they are the &quot;master of no one&quot;, and end up too weak.<br>
<br>
With the skalds (and other music classes, all differently and in their respective domains), Mythic got right on the target, providing us truly versatile classes, able to hold their own in a varity of situations yet definitively weaker than their more specialized counterparts, of course, which is a perfect exemple of game balance. Added to this versatility : niche abilities (speed song, and to a lesser extend damage song) that allows us an almost guaranteed place in every group. <br>
<br>
The consequence is a class that is reasonably powerful in PvE solo (though it slows down at 40+, it is still a viable solo class if not outstanding), extremely wanted in PvE groups (though there are some &quot;skald stacking&quot; issues), able to solo RvR reasonably well (though not as good as the infamous assassin or archer classes), and priceless in group RvR (though we are mostly useless in keep defense and taking situations, we only really shine in skirmishes).<br>
<br>
All of this leads to a balanced, diverse and rewarding class.<br>
